<DOC><DOCNO> AP890530-0125 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1426EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Bush-Students     05-30 0254</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Bush-Students,240</SECOND><HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD><HEAD>Bush Ends Summit Stay With Visit to American School</HEAD><DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush told U.S. studentsTuesday that western values of democracy and freedom ``are winningthe battle around the world'' as he concluded his NATO summit visitwith a stop at an American school.   ``As we look at Eastern Europe and we look at other placesaround the world we see that it's the American values that areprevailing,'' Bush told about 500 high school students at theBrussels American School.   The president and his wife, Barbara, spent about 20 minutes atthe school, located on the outskirts of the city, before leavingfor West Germany, the next stop on their European trip.   The flag-waving students greeted the couple with cheers andapplause.   ``I love this enthusiasm ... Anything to get out of school,''joked the president after the cheering had died down.   In his remarks, Bush only mentioned the NATO summit briefly,saying: ``One of the things that has been marvelous about thissummit is the understanding that our values, the alliance's values... are winning the battle around the world.''   On a lighter note, he read two welcome cards from elementaryschool students.   One began: ``Yo, President Bush. I think you are really cool.''   Looking up from the card to say, ``I want the press to hearthis,'' Bush then continued reading:   ``You make all the right decisions. And I am glad you are comingto our school. I love your hair.''</TEXT></DOC>